		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=61546"><span id="Sage">Slipskin</span></a><b><span id="Sage"><br>Sage</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />1262 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [2.59]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Slipskin&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>Folks, we have it straight from the horses mouth - that is to say - SoE's EQ staff.&nbsp;&nbsp;CHA does not make your mezz or charm more effective or last longer.  What it does do is reduce the chance that the target will aggro on you after a failed lull attempt.  That's it.   (OK, CHA will affect merchant prices, too) <br /> <br />If you pull a lot as a bard then this is good to know.  Otherwise, it means nothing. <br /> <br />A rather good thread on this topic is available at www.EQDiva.com. <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /></p>
